# Title: Fugue in D Dorian for Three Voices
# tempo 78
# Voices: V0 soprano, V1 alto, V2 bass
# Composed dissonance-first from the expanded curriculum:
#   - Subject designed canon-viable at the octave, two beats delay (from
#     canon-at-octave-001), so the finale is a TRUE stretto: alto leads,
#     bass follows in strict canon for the full subject.
#   - Syncopated countersubject: suspension chains ride the answer's and
#     subject's descending tails (9ths above the answer, 7-6 against the
#     bass subject, 4-3 when inverted above the bass answer).
#   - Episode 2 quotes the Fux Dorian cantus in the bass and reuses the
#     verified fourth-species-above-002 solution as the soprano.
#   - Beats 56-57: DELIBERATE voice fusion (parallel octaves S+A) handing
#     the line from soprano to alto; the voice_fusion warning is the
#     intended reading.
#   - Dorian discipline: B natural throughout; C# spent only at the final
#     cadence (beat 74), spiking complexity 77 and releasing into the
#     Picardy D major.
#   0-23   Exposition: subject (alto), answer (soprano) + sync CS (alto),
#          subject (bass) + sync CS with 7-6 chain (soprano)
#   24-31  Episode 1: lament bass descent to the dominant of A
#   32-39  Entry: answer in bass + 4-3 chain CS (alto), free soprano
#   40-47  Episode 2: Fux cantus (bass) under 7-6 suspensions (soprano)
#   48-55  Entry: subject on F (alto), free soprano and bass
#   56-63  Episode 3: fusion handoff S-to-A, descent to dominant pedal
#   64-75  Finale: full canon stretto (alto 64, bass 66), V7 spike, cadence
